Calcium concentration in bird plasma

The file Bird_Plasma.xlsx contains factorial data on blood plasma calcium concentration (Calcium, mg / 100 mL) in male and female birds (Sex) each of which was treated or not with a hormone (Treatment).

Activity

Load the Excel file, and convert hormone and sex to factors. The levels of Treatment are Hormone and None. Because Hormone is first alphabetically, it becomes the base level of the factor. Use fct_relevel from the forcats package to make None the base level.

# FIXME
M <- read_excel("../data/Bird_Plasma.xlsx") |>
  mutate(Treatment = factor(Treatment),
         Sex = factor(Sex),
         Treatment = fct_relevel(Treatment, "None"))

Use group_by() and tally() to determine the sample size in each of the groups.

# FIXME
M |> group_by(Treatment, Sex) |> tally()
## # A tibble: 4  3
## # Groups:   Treatment [2]
##   Treatment Sex        n
##   <fct>     <fct>  <int>
## 1 None      Female     5
## 2 None      Male       5
## 3 Hormone   Female     5
## 4 Hormone   Male       5

Is this a balanced factorial design?

Yes, all combinations of Sex and Treatment are present and all groups have n = 5.

Create interaction plots of the calcium concentration data. Use the code from lecture as a template. Make two plots, one with Treatment on the x axis and one with Sex on the x axis. Use plot_grid() to place them side by side

# FIXME
p1  <- ggplot(M, aes(x = Sex,
              y = Calcium,
              color = Treatment,
              group = Treatment)) +
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 0.1)) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", pch = 5, size = 5) +

p2 <- ggplot(M, aes(x = Treatment,
              y = Calcium,
              color = Sex,
              group = Sex)) +
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(width = 0.1)) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", pch = 5, size = 5) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "line")
cowplot::plot_grid(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

What do you learn from these plots?

Hormone almost certainly has a strong positive effect the lines are very far apart in the first plot. Sexes appear not to differ that much, because the elevations of the lines in the second plot are very similar. Both sexes appear to respond in the same direction and with the same magnitude.

Fit a factorial linear model (both main effects and the interaction term) and save the result to an R object.

# FIXME
fm <- lm(Calcium ~ Sex * Treatment, data = M)

Using the summary() function, determine the R2 for the linear model.

How much of the variance in calcium level can be explained by the predictors?

About 83% of the variance in calcium level is explained by Sex, Treatment, and the Sex by Treatment interaction. 17% of the variance remains unexplained.

Describe the results of the analysis, writing a brief paragraph describing the goal of the analysis, what analysis was carried out, and the results. This is similar to how you would write part of an abstract.

To determine the relative roles of sex and hormone treatment on blood plasma calcium concentration, we used a 2 X 2 factorial design (n = 5 in each group). Factorial ANOVA with the interaction between sex and hormone treatment was analyzed using type III sums of squares. We found a significant effect of hormone treatmen (F1,16 = 41; P < 0.001; R2 = 0.83). Sexes did not differ after controlling for other effects (P = 0.33), including the interaction (P = 0.62).

Effect of predation on zooplankton

The file Zooplankton.csv contains data on the concentration of zooplankton in three predator treatment groups (control, low, and high levels of predators in an enclosure). Each of the three treatments were measured in five replicate blocks.

Activity

Read in the data and convert both Treatment and Block into factors. It is especially important to make sure that Block is a factor, because Blocks are coded 1-5. We need to make sure that R converts them to a model matrix (0s and 1s) rather than using them as numeric 1 to 5, because the numbering is arbitrary (exchangeable in statistical terminology).

# FIXME
M <- read_csv("../data/Zooplankton.csv", col_types = "cdd") |>
  mutate(Treatment = factor(Treatment),
         Block = factor(Block))

Print the data to confirm that each treatment was present in each block.

# FIXME
M
## # A tibble: 15  3
##    Treatment Zooplankton Block
##    <fct>           <dbl> <fct>
##  1 control           4.1 1    
##  2 low               2.2 1    
##  3 high              1.3 1    
##  4 control           3.2 2    
##  5 low               2.4 2    
##  6 high              2   2    
##  7 control           3   3

## 12 high              1   4    
## 13 control           2.5 5    
## 14 low               2.6 5    
## 15 high              1.6 5

This is a very good experimental design, because a multilevel model will allow each block to have its own intercept and assess the difference(s) among treatments as a deviation from the block mean.

An alternative experimental design would be if the researcher had used 15 different plots and randomly assigned them to one of the three treatments. This would also work, but the multilevel block model is more powerful.

Make two plots, one in which Treatment is on the x-axis and Block is encoded by color, and the second in which Block is on the x-axis and Treatment is encoded by color.

# FIXME
M |>
  ggplot(aes(x = Treatment, y = Zooplankton, color = Block)) +
  geom_point()

M |>
  ggplot(aes(x = Block, y = Zooplankton, color = Treatment)) +
  geom_point()

Notice how you learn different things about the data from each of these plots.

Summarize the mean and standard deviation of each group in a table.

# FIXME
M |> 
  group_by(Treatment) |> 
  summarize(Mean = mean(Zooplankton),
            `Std. Dev.` = sd(Zooplankton),
            .groups = "drop") |> 
  knitr::kable(digits = c(2, 2))
Treatment Mean Std. Dev.
control 3.02 0.70
high 1.38 0.43
low 2.00 0.57

We want to test for significant differences in Treatment while accounting for the replicated blocks. We will fit this model using the lme() function from the nlme package with Block as a random effect.

# FIXME
fm_lme <- lme(Zooplankton ~ Treatment,
              random = ~ 1 | Block, M)

Now use anova() to generate the ANOVA table for the model.

# FIXME
anova(fm_lme)
##             numDF denDF   F-value p-value
## (Intercept)     1     8 116.69517  <.0001
## Treatment       2     8  16.36595  0.0015

Is the overall ANOVA significant? You can determine this by examining the Treatment effect (since there is only one predictor).

Yes, the P-value for Treatment is 0.002.

If the overall ANOVA is significant, all we know is that at least one mean is different from the others. Perform a Tukeys HSD post-hoc test on the pairwise combinations of all the levels of Treatment.

Refer to Lecture 08-2 for a reminder of how to code Tukeys HSD with the multcomp package.

# FIXME
tukey <- glht(fm_lme, linfct = mcp(Treatment = "Tukey"))
summary(tukey)
## 
##   Simultaneous Tests for General Linear Hypotheses
## 
## Multiple Comparisons of Means: Tukey Contrasts
## 
## 
## Fit: lme.formula(fixed = Zooplankton ~ Treatment, data = M, random = ~1 | 
##     Block)
## 
## Linear Hypotheses:
##                     Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## high - control == 0  -1.6400     0.2895  -5.665   <0.001 ***
## low - control == 0   -1.0200     0.2895  -3.524   0.0012 ** 
## low - high == 0       0.6200     0.2895   2.142   0.0817 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## (Adjusted p values reported -- single-step method)

Describe the results. Do they make sense biologically?

Overall there is a significant effect of predator level (P = 0.002). The pairwise post-hoc test shows that both high (P < 0.001) and low (P = 0.001) treatments are significantly different than control, but that high and low are not significantly different from each other (P = 0.08). Strangely, both high and low predation levels are associated with lower levels of zooplankton.

Grass Species Richness

At the Conard Environmental Research Area (Grinnell, IA), there are 20 experimental plots with 10 burned each fall and 10 left unburned. The following data are grass species richness data from 5 separate, haphazardly chosen, 10 meter2 plots within each of these 20 experimental plots. The hypothesis to be tested is that burning increases species richness.

# FIXME
set.seed(112)
mms <- c(rnorm(10, 5.5, 2), rnorm(10, 6.5, 2))
all.rich <- numeric(0)
for(ii in mms) {
  all.rich <- c(all.rich, as.integer(rnorm(5, ii, 1)))
}

rich.dat <- data.frame('plot' = as.factor(rep(seq(1, 20), each = 5)), 
                       'treatment' = rep(c('burned', 'unburned'), each = 50), 
                       'richness' = all.rich)
write.table(rich.dat, file="../data/richness.txt",
            sep="\t", row.names = FALSE)

Activity

Load in the richness data (richness.txt), which is a tab-delimited text file (use read_delim() and look at the help to determine how to set the field delimiter to tab). Plot species richness vs.treatment. Include an appropriate amount of jitter and transparency and color points by plot.

rich.dat <- read_delim("../data/richness.txt",
                       col_types = "dcd",
                       delim = "\t") |> 
  mutate(plot = factor(plot))

ggplot(rich.dat, aes(x = treatment, y = richness, color = plot)) +
  geom_point(position = position_jitter(0.1), alpha = 0.5) +
    guides(colour = guide_legend(ncol = 2, byrow = FALSE))

Do you think there is a relationship between species richness and burning?

Probably not. It doesnt look like a strong relationship.

First, fit a model predicting species richness from treatment without considering plot membership.

What can you conclude from the results of this model?

It is difficult to interpret without considering plot as there is pseudoreplication.

Now, calculate the mean species richness value for each plot. Fit a model predicting mean species richness from treatment. This is how you would approach this statistical problem if you did not want to use a multilevel model.

mean.plot <- rich.dat |>
  group_by(plot, treatment) |>
  summarize(meanrich = mean(richness),
            .groups = "drop")
anova(lm(meanrich ~ treatment, data = mean.plot))
## Analysis of Variance Table

What can you conclude from this model?

There is no effect of treatment on species richness.

Use the lme() function to fit a model predicting richness from treatment with plot as a random effect.

summary(lme(richness ~ treatment, random = ~1 | plot,

Compare your results to the approach using the mean value. What can you conclude from this model?

The results are consistent with the model using the mean values. This will not necesarily always happen.

Why would you use lme() versus means per group?

The multilevel model is preferred because it includes all the variation associated with replicate plots. By calculating and using only the means, all the plot-to-plot variation is ignored. Furthermore, there are many patterns of variation than can give the same mean values.

These 20 plots exist in an alternating pattern going from south to north on either side of an access road. What other source of non-independence should you consider? How would you account for this factor?

The spatial relationship between plots needs to be accounted for. You could include a continuous variable coding for position along the south to north axis and/or side of the road.
